  <title>ERA vs Wins Scatterplot</title>
  <dc:creator>Carson Jasa</dc:creator>
  <link>https://your-website-url.example.com/posts/mlb-pitching-wins-era-difference/</link>
  <description><![CDATA[ 





<p>When we think of pitchers in baseball, our minds correlate a good pitcher with a low ERA with wins. Wins is a weird stat in baseball. According to the rule book of Major League Baseball “a starting pitcher must pitch at least five innings (in a traditional game of nine innings or longer) to qualify for the win”. But there’s a catch “A pitcher receives a win when he is the pitcher of record when his team takes the lead for good”.</p>
<p>To put things in simpler terms, a starting pitcher can only get the win if they pitch at least 5 innings AND have offensive support with a lead when they exit the game… AND your team must hold on to the lead for the rest of the game once you exit.</p>
<p>So not only does a starting pitcher’s win statistic rely on his offense to first off score more runs than the other team while he’s pitching, the relief pitchers after him have to record a hold on the opposition.</p>
<p>Let’s look at Baseball’s finest from the 2024 season. And how their wins and ERA compare.</p>
